# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mediterranean
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mediterranean/adjective] An **adjective** (abbreviated **ADJ**) is a word that describes or defines a noun or noun phrase.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Its semantic role is to change information given by the noun.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] The adjective is considered one of the main parts of speech of the English language, although historically they were classed together with nouns.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Nowadays, certain words that usually had been classified as adjectives, including *the*, *this*, *my*, etc., typically are classed separately, as determiners.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Depending on the language, an adjective can precede a corresponding noun on a prepositive basis or it can follow a corresponding noun on a postpositive basis.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Structural, contextual, and style considerations can impinge on the pre-or post-position of an adjective in a given instance of its occurrence.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Adjectives feature as a part of speech (word class) in most languages.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] In some languages, the words that serve the semantic function of adjectives are categorized together with some other class, such as nouns or verbs.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] In the phrase *a Ford car*, *Ford* is unquestionably a noun but its function is adjectival (noun adjunct, see below): to modify *car*.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] In some languages adjectives can function as nouns: for example, the Spanish phrase *un rojo* means 'a red [one]'.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] This is also possible in English, see above.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] As for "confusion" with verbs, rather than an adjective meaning "big", a language might have a verb that means "to be big" and could then use an attributive verb construction analogous to "big-being house" to express what in English is called a "big house".
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Such an analysis is possible for the grammar of Standard Chinese and Korean, for example.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Different languages do not use adjectives in exactly the same situations.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] For example, where English uses *"*to be *hungry*" (*hungry* being an adjective), Dutch, French, and Spanish use "*honger hebben*", "*avoir faim*", and "*tener hambre*" respectively (literally "to have hunger", the words for "hunger" being nouns).
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Similarly, where Hebrew uses the adjective זקוק‎ (*zaqūq*, roughly "in need of" or "needing"), English uses the verb "to need".
[src:mediterranean/adjective] In languages that have adjectives as a word class, it is usually an open class; that is, it is relatively common for new adjectives to be formed via such processes as derivation.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] However, Bantu languages are well known for having only a small closed class of adjectives, and new adjectives are not easily derived.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Similarly, native Japanese adjectives (*i*-adjectives) are considered a closed class (as are native verbs), although nouns (an open class) may be used in the genitive to convey some adjectival meanings, and there is also the separate open class of adjectival nouns (*na*-adjectives).
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Many languages (including English) distinguish between adjectives, which qualify nouns and pronouns, and adverbs, which mainly modify verbs, adjectives, or other adverbs.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Not all languages make this exact distinction; many (including English) have words that can function as either.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] For example, in English, *fast* is an adjective in "a *fast* car" (where it qualifies the noun *car*) but an adverb in "he drove *fast*" (where it modifies the verb *drove*).
[src:mediterranean/adjective] A German word like *klug* ("clever(ly)") takes endings when used as an attributive adjective but not when used adverbially.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Whether these are distinct parts of speech or distinct usages of the same part of speech is a question of analysis.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] While German linguistic terminology distinguishes *adverbiale* from *adjektivische Formen*, German refers to both as *Eigenschaftswörter* ("property words").
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Linguists today distinguish determiners from adjectives, considering them to be two separate parts of speech (or *lexical categories*).
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Determiners formerly were considered to be adjectives in some of their uses.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Determiners function neither as nouns nor pronouns but instead characterize a nominal element within a particular context.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] They generally do this by indicating definiteness (*a* vs.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] An adjective acts as the head of an *adjective phrase* or *adjectival phrase* (AP).
[src:mediterranean/adjective] In the simplest case, an adjective phrase consists solely of the adjective; more complex adjective phrases may contain one or more adverbs modifying the adjective ("*very* strong"), or one or more complements (such as "worth *several dollars*", "full *of toys*", or "eager *to please*").
[src:mediterranean/adjective] In English, attributive adjective phrases that include complements typically follow the noun that they qualify ("an evildoer *devoid of redeeming qualities*").
[src:mediterranean/adjective] In many languages (including English) it is possible for nouns to modify other nouns.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Unlike adjectives, nouns acting as modifiers (called *attributive nouns* or *noun adjuncts*) usually are not predicative; a beautiful park is beautiful, but a car park is not "car".
[src:mediterranean/adjective] The modifier often indicates origin ("*Virginia* reel"), purpose ("*work* clothes"), semantic patient ("*man* eater") or semantic subject ("*child* actor"); however, it may generally indicate almost any semantic relationship.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] It is also common for adjectives to be derived from nouns, as in *boyish*, *birdlike*, *behavioral (behavioural)*, *famous*, *manly*, *angelic*, and so on.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Many languages have participle forms that can act as noun modifiers either alone or as the head of a phrase.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Sometimes participles develop into functional usage as adjectives.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Examples in English include *relieved* (the past participle of *relieve*), used as an adjective in passive voice constructs such as "I am so *relieved* to see you".
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Other examples include *spoken* (the past participle of *speak*) and *going* (the present participle of *go*), which function as attribute adjectives in such phrases as "the *spoken* word" and "the *going* rate".
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Other constructs that often modify nouns include prepositional phrases (as in "a rebel *without a cause*"), relative clauses (as in "the man *who wasn't there*"), and infinitive phrases (as in "a cake *to die for*").
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Some nouns can also take complements such as content clauses (as in "the idea *that I would do that*"), but these are not commonly considered modifiers.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] For more information about possible modifiers and dependents of nouns, see Components of noun phrases.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] In Australian Aboriginal languages, the distinction between adjectives and nouns is typically thought weak, and many of the languages only use nouns, or nouns with a limited set of adjective-deriving affixes, to modify other nouns.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] In languages that have a subtle adjective-noun distinction, one way to tell them apart is that a modifying adjective can come to stand in for an entire elided noun phrase, while a modifying noun cannot.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] For example, in Bardi, the adjective *moorrooloo* 'little' in the phrase *moorrooloo* *baawa* 'little child' can stand on its own to mean 'the little one', while the attributive noun *aamba* 'man' in the phrase *aamba baawa* 'male child' cannot stand for the whole phrase to mean 'the male one'.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] In other languages, like Warlpiri, nouns and adjectives are lumped together beneath the nominal umbrella because of their shared syntactic distribution as arguments of predicates.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] The only thing distinguishing them is that some nominals seem to semantically denote entities (typically nouns in English) and some nominals seem to denote attributes (typically adjectives in English).
[src:mediterranean/adjective] In many languages, attributive adjectives usually occur in a specific order.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] In general, the adjective order in English can be summarised as: opinion, size, age or shape, colour, origin, material, purpose.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Other language authorities, like the *Cambridge Dictionary*, state that shape precedes rather than follows age.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Determiners and postdeterminers—articles, numerals, and other limiters (e.g.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] *three* blind mice)—come before attributive adjectives in English.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Although certain combinations of determiners can appear before a noun, they are far more circumscribed than adjectives in their use—typically, only a single determiner would appear before a noun or noun phrase (including any attributive adjectives).
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Size – adjectives denoting physical size (e.g.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Shape or physical quality – adjectives describing more detailed physical attributes than overall size (e.g.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Colour – adjectives denoting colour or pattern (e.g.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Origin – denominal adjectives denoting source (e.g.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] This means that, in English, adjectives pertaining to size precede adjectives pertaining to age ("little old", not "old little"), which in turn generally precede adjectives pertaining to colour ("old white", not "white old").
[src:mediterranean/adjective] This order may be more rigid in some languages than others; in some, like Spanish, it may only be a default (*unmarked*) word order, with other orders being permissible.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Other languages, such as Tagalog, follow their adjectival orders as rigidly as English.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] The normal adjectival order of English may be overridden in certain circumstances, especially when one adjective is being fronted or with ablaut reduplication.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] For example, the usual order of adjectives in English would result in the phrase "the bad big wolf" (opinion before size), but instead, the usual phrase is "the big bad wolf".
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Owing partially to borrowings from French, English has some adjectives that follow the noun as postmodifiers, called postpositive adjectives, as in *time immemorial* and *attorney general*.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Adjectives may even change meaning depending on whether they precede or follow, as in *proper*: "They live in a *proper town*" (a real town, not a village) vs.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] "They live in the *town proper* (in the town itself, not in the suburbs).
[src:mediterranean/adjective] In many languages, some adjectives are *comparable* and the measure of comparison is called *degree*.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] For example, a person may be "polite", but another person may be "*more* polite", and a third person may be the "*most* polite" of the three.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] The word "more" here modifies the adjective "polite" to indicate a comparison is being made, and "most" modifies the adjective to indicate an absolute comparison (a *superlative*).
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Among languages that allow adjectives to be compared, different means are used to indicate comparison.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Some languages do not distinguish between comparative and superlative forms.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Other languages allow adjectives to be compared but do not have a special comparative form of the adjective.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] In such cases, as in some Australian Aboriginal languages, case-marking, such as the ablative case, may be used to indicate one entity has more of an adjectival quality than (i.e.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Another way to convey comparison is by incorporating the words "more" and "most".
[src:mediterranean/adjective] There is no simple rule to decide which means is correct for any given adjective, however.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] The general tendency is for simpler adjectives and those from Anglo-Saxon to take the suffixes, while longer adjectives and those from French, Latin, or Greek do not—but sometimes the *sound* of the word is the deciding factor.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Many adjectives do not naturally lend themselves to comparison.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] For example, some English speakers would argue that it does not make sense to say that one thing is "more ultimate" than another, or that something is "most ultimate", since the word "ultimate" is already absolute in its semantics.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Such adjectives are called *non-comparable* or *absolute*.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Nevertheless, native speakers will frequently play with the raised forms of adjectives of this sort.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Although "pregnant" is logically non-comparable (either one is pregnant or not), one may hear a sentence like "She looks more and more pregnant each day".
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Comparative and superlative forms are also occasionally used for other purposes than comparison.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] In Italian, superlatives are frequently used to put strong emphasis on an adjective: *bellissimo* means "most beautiful", but is in fact more commonly heard in the sense "extremely beautiful".
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Attributive adjectives and other noun modifiers may be used either *restrictively* (helping to identify the noun's referent, hence "restricting" its reference) or *non-restrictively* (helping to describe a noun).
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Here "difficult" is restrictive – it tells which tasks he avoids, distinguishing these from the easy ones: "Only those tasks that are difficult".
[src:mediterranean/adjective] In English, restrictiveness is not marked on adjectives but is marked on relative clauses (the difference between "the man *who recognized me* was there" and "the man, *who recognized me*, was there" being one of restrictiveness).
[src:mediterranean/adjective] In some languages, adjectives alter their form to reflect the gender, case and number of the noun that they describe.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Here, a distinction may be made between attributive and predicative usage.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] In English, adjectives never agree, whereas in French, they always agree.
[src:mediterranean/adjective] Semanticist Barbara Partee classifies adjectives semantically as intersective, subsective, or nonsubsective, with nonsubsective adjectives being plain nonsubsective or privative.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The **Mediterranean Sea** (/ˌmɛdɪtəˈreɪniən/ *MED-ih-tə-RAY-nee-ən*) is an intercontinental sea situated between Europe, Asia, and Africa.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] It is surrounded by the Mediterranean basin and almost completely enclosed by land: on the east by the Levant in West Asia, on the north by Anatolia in West Asia and Southern Europe, and on the south by North Africa.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Mediterranean Sea covers an area of about 2,500,000 km2 (970,000 sq mi), representing 0.7% of the global ocean surface; it includes fifteen marginal seas, including the Aegean, Adriatic, Tyrrhenian, and Marmara.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Geological evidence indicates that around 5.9 million years ago, the Mediterranean was cut off from the Atlantic and was partly or completely desiccated over a period of some 600,000 years during the Messinian salinity crisis before being refilled by the Zanclean flood about 5.3 million years ago.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Levant in the Eastern Mediterranean was among the first regions in the world to display permanent human habitation as early as 12,000 BC.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Mediterranean Sea was an important route for merchants, travellers, and migrants in antiquity, facilitating trade and cultural exchange between various peoples as well as colonisation and conquest.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Roman Empire maintained nautical hegemony over the sea for centuries and is the only state to have ever controlled all of its coast.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Mediterranean Sea has an average depth of 1,500 m (4,900 ft) and the deepest recorded point is 5,109 ± 1 m (16,762 ± 3 ft) in the Calypso Deep in the Ionian Sea.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] It lies between latitudes 30° and 46° N and longitudes 6° W and 36° E.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Its west–east length, from the Strait of Gibraltar to the Gulf of Alexandretta, on the southeastern coast of Turkey, is about 4,000 kilometres (2,500 mi).
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The north–south length varies greatly between different shorelines and whether only straight routes are considered.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Also including longitudinal changes, the shortest shipping route between the multinational Gulf of Trieste and the Libyan coastline of the Gulf of Sidra is about 1,900 kilometres (1,200 mi).
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The water temperatures are mild in winter and warm in summer and give name to the Mediterranean climate type due to the majority of precipitation falling in the cooler months.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Its southern and eastern coastlines are lined with hot deserts not far inland, but the immediate coastline on all sides of the Mediterranean tends to have strong maritime moderation.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] In addition, Northern Cyprus (de facto state) and two overseas territories of the United Kingdom (Akrotiri and Dhekelia, and Gibraltar) also have coastlines along the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The drainage basin encompasses a large number of other countries, the Nile being the longest river ending in the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Mediterranean Sea encompasses a vast number of islands, some of them of volcanic origin.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The two largest islands, in both area and population, are Sicily and Sardinia.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Major ancient civilizations were located around the Mediterranean.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The sea provided routes for trade, colonization, and war, as well as food (from fishing and the gathering of other seafood) for numerous communities throughout the ages.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The earliest advanced civilizations in the Mediterranean were the Egyptians and the Minoans, who traded extensively with each other.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Around 1200 BC the eastern Mediterranean was greatly affected by the Bronze Age Collapse, which resulted in the destruction of many cities and trade routes.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Two other notable Mediterranean civilizations in classical antiquity are the Greek city-states and Phoenicians, both of whom extensively colonized the coastlines of the Mediterranean.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Darius I of Persia, who conquered Ancient Egypt, built a canal linking the Red Sea to the Nile, and thus the Mediterranean.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Darius's canal was wide enough for two triremes to pass each other with oars extended and required four days to traverse.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Following the Punic Wars in the 3rd and 2nd centuries BC, the Roman Republic defeated the Carthaginians to become the preeminent power in the Western Mediterranean region.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] When Augustus founded the Roman Empire, the Romans referred to the Mediterranean as *Mare Nostrum* ("Our Sea").
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] For the next 400 years, the Roman Empire completely controlled the Mediterranean Sea and virtually all its coastal regions from Gibraltar to the Levant, giving the sea the nickname "Roman Lake".
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Western Roman Empire collapsed around 476 AD.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The east was again dominant as Roman power still existed on in the Byzantine Empire formed in the 4th century from the eastern half of the Roman Empire.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] During that time, another power arose in the 7th century, and with it the religion of Islam, which soon swept across from the east; at its greatest extent, the Arabs, under the Umayyads, controlled the Iberian Peninsula, making a new phase of art and culture in the region.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] A variety of foodstuffs, spices and crops were introduced to the western Mediterranean's Spain and Sicily during Arab rule, via the commercial networks of the Islamic world.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] These include sugarcane, rice, cotton, alfalfa, oranges, lemons, apricots, spinach, eggplants, carrots, saffron and bananas.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Arabs also continued extensive cultivation and production of olive oil (the Spanish words for 'oil' and 'olive'—*aceite* and *aceituna*, respectively—are derived from the Arabic *al-zait*, meaning 'olive juice'), and pomegranates (the heraldic symbol of Granada) from classical Greco-Roman times.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Arab invasions disrupted the trade relations between Western and Eastern Europe while disrupting trade routes with Eastern Asian Empires.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] This, however, had the indirect effect of promoting trade across the Caspian Sea.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The export of grains from Egypt was re-routed towards the Eastern world.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Products from East Asian empires, like silk and spices, were carried from Egypt to ports like Venice and Constantinople by sailors and Jewish merchants.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Viking raids further disrupted the trade in western Europe and brought it to a halt.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] However, the Norsemen developed the trade from Norway to the White Sea, while also trading in luxury goods from Spain and the Mediterranean.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Byzantines in the mid-8th century retook control of the area around the north-eastern part of the Mediterranean.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Venetian ships from the 9th century armed themselves to counter the harassment by Arabs while concentrating trade of Asian goods in Venice.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Fatimids maintained trade relations with the Italian city-states like Amalfi and Genoa before the Crusades, according to the Cairo Geniza documents.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] A document dated 996 mentions Amalfian merchants living in Cairo.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Another letter states that the Genoese had traded with Alexandria.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The caliph al-Mustansir had allowed Amalfian merchants to reside in Jerusalem about 1060 in place of the Latin hospice.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Crusades led to the flourishing of trade between Europe and the *outremer* region.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Genoa, Venice and Pisa created colonies in regions controlled by the Crusaders and came to control the trade with the Orient.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] These colonies also allowed them to trade with the Eastern world.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Though the fall of the Crusader states and attempts at banning of trade relations with Muslim states by the Popes temporarily disrupted the trade with the Orient, it however continued.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Europe started to revive, however, when there was gradual centralization of state power in the Renaissance of the 12th century.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Ottoman power based in Anatolia continued to grow, and in 1453 extinguished the Byzantine Empire with the Conquest of Constantinople.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Hayreddin Barbarossa, the Ottoman captain is a symbol of this domination with the victory of the Battle of Preveza (1538), opening up Tripoli and the eastern Mediterranean to Ottoman rule.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] As the naval prowess of the European powers increased, they confronted Ottoman expansion in the region when the Battle of Lepanto (1571) damaging the power of the Ottoman Navy.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] This was the last naval battle to be fought primarily between galleys.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Barbary pirates of Northwest Africa preyed on Christian shipping and coastlines in the Western Mediterranean Sea.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] According to Robert Davis, from the 16th to 19th centuries, pirates captured 1 million to 1.25 million Europeans as slaves.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The development of oceanic shipping began to affect the entire Mediterranean.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Once, most of the trade between Western Europe and the East was passing through the region, but after the 1490s the development of a sea route to the Indian Ocean allowed the importation of Asian spices and other goods through the Atlantic ports of western Europe.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The sea remained strategically important.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] British mastery of Gibraltar ensured their influence in Africa and Southwest Asia.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Especially after the naval battles of Abukir (1799, Battle of the Nile) and Trafalgar (1805), the British had for a long time strengthened their dominance in the Mediterranean.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Wars included Naval warfare in the Mediterranean during World War I and Mediterranean theatre of World War II.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] With the opening of the lockless Suez Canal in 1869, the flow of trade between Europe and Asia changed fundamentally.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The fastest route now led through the Mediterranean towards East Africa and Asia.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] This led to a preference for the Mediterranean countries and their ports like Trieste with direct connections to Central and Eastern Europe experienced a rapid economic rise.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] In the 20th century, the 1st and 2nd World Wars as well as the Suez Crisis and the Cold War led to a shift of trade routes to the European northern ports, which changed again towards the southern ports through European integration, the activation of the Silk Road and free world trade.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] In 2013, the Maltese president described the Mediterranean Sea as a "cemetery" due to the large number of migrants who drowned there after their boats capsized.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] European Parliament president Martin Schulz said in 2014 that Europe's migration policy "turned the Mediterranean into a graveyard", referring to the number of drowned refugees in the region as a direct result of the policies.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] An Azerbaijani official described the sea as "a burial ground ... where people die".
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] In 2015, more than one million migrants crossed the Mediterranean Sea into Europe.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Italy was particularly affected by the European migrant crisis.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Between 2013 and 2018, over 700,000 migrants landed in Italy, mainly sub-Saharan Africans.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] A satellite image showing the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The 163 km (101 mi) long artificial Suez Canal in the southeast connects the Mediterranean Sea to the Red Sea without ship lock, because the water level is essentially the same.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Note 1: The International Hydrographic Organization defines the area as generic Mediterranean Sea, in the Western Basin.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] It does not recognize the label Sea of Sardinia.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Note 2: Thracian Sea, Icarian Sea, Sea of Crete and Myrtoan Sea are seas that are part of the Aegean Sea.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Note 3: The Black Sea is not considered part of it.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The drainage basin of the Mediterranean Sea is particularly heterogeneous and extends much further than the Mediterranean region.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Its size has been estimated between 4,000,000 and 5,500,000 km2 (1,500,000 and 2,100,000 sq mi), depending on whether non-active parts (deserts) are included or not.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The longest river ending in the Mediterranean Sea is the Nile, which takes its sources in equatorial Africa.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The basin of the Nile constitutes about two-thirds of the Mediterranean drainage basin and encompasses areas as high as the Ruwenzori Mountains.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Among other important rivers in Africa, are the Moulouya and the Chelif, both on the north side of the Atlas Mountains.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] In Asia, are the Ceyhan and Seyhan, both on the south side of the Taurus Mountains.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] In Europe, the largest basins are those of the Rhône, Ebro, Po, and Maritsa.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The basin of the Rhône is the largest and extends up as far north as the Jura Mountains, encompassing areas even on the north side of the Alps.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The basins of the Ebro, Po, and Maritsa, are respectively south of the Pyrenees, Alps, and Balkan Mountains, which are the major ranges bordering Southern Europe.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Total annual precipitation is significantly higher on the European part of the Mediterranean basin, especially near the Alps (the 'water tower of Europe') and other high mountain ranges.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] As a consequence, the river discharges of the Rhône and Po are similar to that of the Nile, despite the latter having a much larger basin.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] These are the only three rivers with an average discharge of over 1,000 m3/s (35,000 cu ft/s).
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Among large natural fresh bodies of water are Lake Victoria (Nile basin), Lake Geneva (Rhône), and the Italian Lakes (Po).
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] While the Mediterranean watershed is bordered by other river basins in Europe, it is essentially bordered by endorheic basins or deserts elsewhere.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Mediterranean Sea encompasses about 10,000 islands and islets, of which about 250 are permanently inhabited.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] In the table below are listed the ten largest by population.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Much of the Mediterranean coast has a hot-summer Mediterranean climate.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Mediterranean basin has a climate characterised by mild wet winters, and calm, dry and hot summers.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Although they are rare, tropical cyclones occasionally form in the Mediterranean Sea, typically in September–November.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Mediterranean Sea has numerous underwater geological features formed by the subduction of the African Plate beneath the Eurasian Plate.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The sea is divided naturally into western and eastern regions by the Malta Escarpment that runs from the island of Sicily to the African coast.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Until the 1960s, the Mediterranean was believed to be the primary remaining portion of the earlier (200 million years old) Mesozoic Tethys Ocean, which once encircled the Eastern Hemisphere.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] However, since the late 20th century, research using the theory of seafloor spreading has indicated that most of the current Mediterranean seafloor is not a portion of the Tethys sea floor.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Some researchers consider the Ionian Basin, to the east of the Malta Escarpment, to be the remnant of the Tethys Ocean.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Over the course of the last 44 million years, the continental plates of Africa and Eurasia have converged and receded, resulting in the current tectonically active basin and its surrounding mountain chains.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] According to the interpretation of geologic data, there are currently several major places where Africa and Eurasia collide, causing land submergence, mountain building, and volcanism.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Sediment cores drilled in 1970 and 1975 led to theories that about 6 million years ago, the Mediterranean was around 3,000 metres (10,000 ft) below the current sea level and included arid deserts blanketed with evaporite salts.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] It was thought that Gibraltar's high ridges prevented Atlantic waters from entering until roughly 5.5 million years ago, when they broke through and flooded the Mediterranean.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] According to more recent seismic and microfossil research, the seafloor was never entirely dry.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Rather, approximately 5 million years ago, the seafloor was made up of many basins with varying topography and sizes, spanning in depth from 200 to 1,520 metres (650 to 5,000 ft).
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Salts were likely accumulated on the bottom of highly salinised waters of widely differing depths.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The uncertainty of the timing and nature of sea-bottom salt formation and evidence from later seismic research and core samples has been the subject of intense scientific debate.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Malta Escarpment is a 250-kilometre (160 mi) undersea limestone escarpment that stretches south from Sicily's eastern coast to the Maltese islands' eastern coast and beyond, primarily formed due to tectonic activities.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] There are more than 500 undersea canyons along the cliffs, which can reach heights of 3.5 kilometres (2.2 mi) in some locations.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Rich biological communities may be found in the canyons, which also serve as channels for contaminants and nutrients due to underwater currents.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] These deep valleys are special due to the fact that they were not carved out by surface rivers.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Underwater landslides are among the natural hazards found on the Malta Escarpment.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Evaporation greatly exceeds precipitation and river runoff in the Mediterranean, a fact that is central to the water circulation within the basin.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Evaporation is especially high in its eastern half, causing the water level to decrease and salinity to increase eastward.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The average salinity in the basin is 38 PSU at 5 m (16 ft) depth.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The temperature of the water in the deepest part of the Mediterranean Sea is 13.2 °C (55.8 °F).
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The net water influx from the Atlantic Ocean is ca.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Without this Atlantic water, the sea level of the Mediterranean Sea would fall at a rate of about 1 m (3 ft) per year.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] In oceanography, it is sometimes called the *Eurafrican Mediterranean Sea*, the *European Mediterranean Sea* or the *African Mediterranean Sea* to distinguish it from mediterranean seas elsewhere, like the Baltic Sea, and the North-east Atlantic Ocean.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Water circulation in the Mediterranean can be attributed to the surface waters entering from the Atlantic through the Strait of Gibraltar (and also low salinity water entering the Mediterranean from the Black Sea through the Bosphorus).
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The cool and relatively low-salinity Atlantic water circulates eastwards along the North African coasts.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] A part of the surface water does not pass the Strait of Sicily, but deviates towards Corsica before exiting the Mediterranean.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The surface waters entering the eastern Mediterranean Basin circulate along the Libyan and Israeli coasts.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Upon reaching the Levantine Sea, the surface water, having warmed and increased its salinity from its initial Atlantic state, is now denser and sinks to form the Levantine Intermediate Waters (LIW).
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Most of the water found anywhere between 50 and 600 m (160 and 2,000 ft) deep in the Mediterranean originates from the LIW.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] LIW are formed along the coasts of Turkey and circulate westwards along the Greek and south Italian coasts.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] LIW are the only waters passing the Sicily Strait westwards.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] After the Strait of Sicily, the LIW circulate along the Italian, French and Spanish coasts before exiting the Mediterranean through the depths of the Strait of Gibraltar.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Deep water in the Mediterranean originates from three main areas: the Adriatic Sea, from which most of the deep water in the eastern Mediterranean originates, the Aegean Sea, and the Gulf of Lion.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Deep water formation in the Mediterranean is triggered by strong winter convection fuelled by intense cold winds like Bora and Mistral.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] When new deep water is formed, the older waters mix with the overlaying intermediate waters and eventually exit the Mediterranean.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The residence time of water in the Mediterranean is approximately 100 years, making the Mediterranean especially sensitive to climate change (see below).
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Being a semi-enclosed basin, the Mediterranean experiences transitory events that can affect the water circulation on short time scales.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] In the mid-1990s, the Aegean Sea became the main area for deep water formation in the eastern Mediterranean after particularly cold winter conditions.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] This transitory switch in the origin of deep waters in the eastern Mediterranean was termed Eastern Mediterranean Transient (EMT) and had major consequences on water circulation of the Mediterranean.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Another example of a transient event affecting the Mediterranean circulation is the periodic inversion of the North Ionian Gyre, which is an anticyclonic ocean gyre observed in the northern part of the Ionian Sea, off the Greek coast.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The transition from anticyclonic to cyclonic rotation of this gyre changes the origin of the waters fuelling it; when the circulation is anticyclonic (most common), the waters of the gyre originate from the Adriatic Sea.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] When the circulation is cyclonic, the waters originate from the Levantine Sea.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] These waters have different physical and chemical characteristics, and the periodic inversion of the North Ionian Gyre (called Bimodal Oscillating System or BiOS) changes the Mediterranean circulation and biogeochemistry around the Adriatic and Levantine regions.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Because of the short residence time of its waters, the Mediterranean Sea is considered a hot-spot for climate change records, registering indeed marked increases in temperature across the entire water column since the 1950s.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] According to climate projections, the decrease in precipitation over the region will lead to more evaporation, ultimately increasing marine salinity.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] As a result of both temperature and salinity increases, the Mediterranean Sea is likely to become more stratified by the end of the 21st century, with notable consequences on water circulation and biogeochemistry.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The stratification and warming have already led the eastern Mediterranean to become a net source of CO2 to the atmosphere.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] These events, mainly driven by a combination of oceanic and atmospheric factors, are often triggered by high pressure systems that will reduce cloud cover and increase solar absorption by the sea surface.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Their impacts on marine ecosystems, such as mass mortality in benthic communities, coral bleaching events, disruptions in fishery catches and shifts in species distributions, can be devastating.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Extreme warming can lead to biodiversity loss and presents an existential threat to some habitats while making conditions more hospitable to invasive tropical species.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] In spite of its great biodiversity, concentrations of chlorophyll and nutrients in the Mediterranean Sea are very low, making it one of the most oligotrophic ocean regions in the world.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Mediterranean Sea is commonly referred to as an LNLC (Low-Nutrient, Low-Chlorophyll) area.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Mediterranean Sea fits the definition of a desert in which its nutrient contents are low, making it difficult for plants and animals to develop.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] There are steep gradients in nutrient concentrations, chlorophyll concentrations and primary productivity in the Mediterranean.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Nutrient concentrations in the western part of the basin are about double the concentrations in the eastern basin.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Alboran Sea, close to the Strait of Gibraltar, has a daily primary productivity of about 0.25 g C (grams of carbon) m−2 day−1 whereas the eastern basin has an average daily productivity of 0.16 g C m−2 day−1.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] For this reason, the eastern part of the Mediterranean Sea is termed "ultraoligotrophic".
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The productive areas of the Mediterranean Sea are few and small.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] High (i.e. more than 0.5 grams of Chlorophyll *a* per cubic metre) productivity occurs in coastal areas, close to the river mouths which are the primary suppliers of dissolved nutrients.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The Gulf of Lion has a relatively high productivity because it is an area of high vertical mixing, bringing nutrients to the surface waters that can be used by phytoplankton to produce Chlorophyll *a*.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Primary productivity in the Mediterranean is also marked by an intense seasonal variability.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] In winter, the strong winds and precipitation over the basin generate vertical mixing, bringing nutrients from the deep waters to the surface, where phytoplankton can convert it into biomass.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] However, in winter, light may be the limiting factor for primary productivity.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Between March and April, spring offers the ideal trade-off between light intensity and nutrient concentrations in surface for a spring bloom to occur.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] In summer, high atmospheric temperatures lead to the warming of the surface waters.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] The resulting density difference virtually isolates the surface waters from the rest of the water column and nutrient exchanges are limited.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] As a consequence, primary productivity is very low between June and October.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Oceanographic expeditions uncovered a characteristic feature of the Mediterranean Sea biogeochemistry: most of the chlorophyll production does not occur on the surface, but in sub-surface waters between 80 and 200 metres deep.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Another key characteristic of the Mediterranean is its high nitrogen-to-phosphorus ratio (N:P).
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Redfield demonstrated that most of the world's oceans have an average N:P ratio around 16.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] However, the Mediterranean Sea has an average N:P between 24 and 29, which translates a widespread phosphorus limitation.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p01] Because of its low productivity, plankton assemblages in the Mediterranean Sea are dominated by small organisms such as picophytoplankton and bacteria.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The geologic history of the Mediterranean Sea is complex.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Because it is a near-landlocked body of water in a normally dry climate, the Mediterranean is subject to intensive evaporation and the precipitation of evaporites.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The Messinian salinity crisis started about six million years ago (mya) when the Mediterranean became landlocked, and then essentially dried up.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] There are salt deposits accumulated on the bottom of the basin of more than a million cubic kilometres—in some places more than three kilometres thick.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Scientists estimate that the sea was last filled about 5.3 million years ago (mya) in less than two years by the Zanclean flood.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Water poured in from the Atlantic Ocean through a newly breached gateway now called the Strait of Gibraltar at an estimated rate of about three orders of magnitude (one thousand times) larger than the current flow of the Amazon River.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The Mediterranean Sea has an average depth of 1,500 m (4,900 ft) and the deepest recorded point is 5,267 m (17,280 ft) in the Calypso Deep in the Ionian Sea.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] A shallow submarine ridge (the Strait of Sicily) between the island of Sicily and the coast of Tunisia divides the sea in two main subregions: the Western Mediterranean, with an area of about 850,000 km2 (330,000 sq mi); and the Eastern Mediterranean, of about 1.65 million km2 (640,000 sq mi).
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Coastal areas have submarine karst springs or *vrulja*s, which discharge pressurised groundwater into the water from below the surface; the discharge water is usually fresh, and sometimes may be thermal.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] During Mesozoic and Cenozoic times, as the northwest corner of Africa converged on Iberia, it lifted the Betic-Rif mountain belts across southern Iberia and northwest Africa.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] There the development of the intramontane Betic and Rif basins created two roughly parallel marine gateways between the Atlantic Ocean and the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Dubbed the Betic and Rifian corridors, they gradually closed during the middle and late Miocene: perhaps several times.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] In the late Miocene the closure of the Betic Corridor triggered the so-called "Messinian salinity crisis" (MSC), characterised by the deposition of a thick evaporitic sequence – with salt deposits up to 2 km thick in the Levantine sea – and by a massive drop in water level in much of the Basin.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] This event was for long the subject of acute scientific controversy, now much appeased, regarding its sequence, geographic range, processes leading to evaporite facies and salt deposits.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The start of the MSC was recently estimated astronomically at 5.96 mya, and it persisted for some 630,000 years until about 5.3 mya; see Animation: Messinian salinity crisis, at right.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] After the initial drawdown and re-flooding, there followed more episodes—the total number is debated—of sea drawdowns and re-floodings for the duration of the MSC.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] It ended when the Atlantic Ocean last re-flooded the basin—creating the Strait of Gibraltar and causing the Zanclean flood—at the end of the Miocene (5.33 mya).
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Some research has suggested that a desiccation-flooding-desiccation cycle may have repeated several times, which could explain several events of large amounts of salt deposition.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Recent studies, however, show that repeated desiccation and re-flooding is unlikely from a geodynamic point of view.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The present-day Atlantic gateway, the Strait of Gibraltar, originated in the early Pliocene via the Zanclean Flood.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] As mentioned, there were two earlier gateways: the Betic Corridor across southern Spain and the Rifian Corridor across northern Morocco.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The Betic closed about 6 mya, causing the Messinian salinity crisis (MSC); the Rifian or possibly both gateways closed during the earlier Tortonian times, causing a "Tortonian salinity crisis" (from 11.6 to 7.2 mya), long before the MSC and lasting much longer.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Both "crises" resulted in broad connections between the mainlands of Africa and Europe, which allowed migrations of flora and fauna—especially large mammals including primates—between the two continents.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The Vallesian crisis indicates a typical extinction and replacement of mammal species in Europe during Tortonian times following climatic upheaval and overland migrations of new species.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] In the 1920s, Herman Sörgel proposed the building of a hydroelectric dam (the Atlantropa project) across the Straits, using the inflow current to provide a large amount of hydroelectric energy.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The underlying energy grid was also intended to support a political union between Europe and, at least, the Maghreb part of Africa (compare Eurafrika for the later impact and Desertec for a later project with some parallels in the planned grid).
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Because of its latitude and its landlocked position, the Mediterranean is especially sensitive to astronomically induced climatic variations, which are well documented in its sedimentary record.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Since the Mediterranean is subject to the deposition of eolian dust from the Sahara during dry periods, whereas riverine detrital input prevails during wet ones, the Mediterranean marine sapropel-bearing sequences provide high-resolution climatic information.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] These data have been employed in reconstructing astronomically calibrated time scales for the last 9 Ma of the Earth's history, helping to constrain the time of past geomagnetic reversals.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Unlike the vast multidirectional ocean currents in open oceans within their respective oceanic zones; biodiversity in the Mediterranean Sea is stable due to the subtle but strong locked nature of currents which is favourable to life, even the smallest macroscopic type of volcanic life form.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The stable marine ecosystem of the Mediterranean Sea and sea temperature provides a nourishing environment for life in the deep sea to flourish while assuring a balanced aquatic ecosystem excluded from any external deep oceanic factors.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] It is estimated that there are more than 17,000 marine species in the Mediterranean Sea with generally higher marine biodiversity in coastal areas, continental shelves, and decreases with depth.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] As a result of the drying of the sea during the Messinian salinity crisis, the marine biota of the Mediterranean is derived primarily from the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The North Atlantic is considerably colder and more nutrient-rich than the Mediterranean, and the marine life of the Mediterranean has had to adapt to its differing conditions in the five million years since the basin was reflooded later.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The Alboran Sea is a transition zone between the two seas, containing a mix of Mediterranean and Atlantic species.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The Mediterranean monk seals live in the Aegean Sea in Greece.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] There was a resident population of orcas in the Mediterranean until the 1980s, when they went extinct, probably due to long-term PCB exposure.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] There are still annual sightings of orca vagrants.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] For 4,000 years, human activity has transformed most parts of Mediterranean Europe, and the "humanisation of the landscape" overlapped with the appearance of the present Mediterranean climate.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The image of a simplistic, environmental determinist notion of a Mediterranean paradise on Earth in antiquity, which was destroyed by later civilisations, dates back to at least the 18th century and was for centuries fashionable in archaeological and historical circles.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The belief stems more from the failure of the recent landscape to measure up to the imaginary past of the classics as idealised by artists, poets and scientists of the early modern Enlightenment.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The historical evolution of climate, vegetation and landscape in southern Europe from prehistoric times to the present is much more complex and underwent various changes.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] For example, some of the deforestation had already taken place before the Roman age.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] While in the Roman age large enterprises such as the latifundia took effective care of forests and agriculture, the largest depopulation effects came with the end of the empire.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The major deforestation might have taken place in modern times—the later usage patterns were also quite different e.g. in southern and northern Italy.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Also, the climate has usually been unstable and there is evidence of various ancient and modern "Little Ice Ages", and plant cover accommodated to various extremes and became resilient to various patterns of human activity.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Even Grove considered that human activity could be the cause of climate change.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Modern science has been able to provide clear evidence of this.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The wide ecological diversity typical of Mediterranean Europe is predominantly based on human behaviour, as it is and has been closely related to human usage patterns.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The diversity range was enhanced by the widespread exchange and interaction of the longstanding and highly diverse local agriculture, intense transport and trade relations, and the interaction with settlements, pasture and other land use.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The greatest human-induced changes, however, came after World War II, in line with the "1950s syndrome" as rural populations throughout the region abandoned traditional subsistence economies.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Grove and Rackham suggest that the locals left the traditional agricultural patterns and instead became scenery-setting agents for tourism.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] This resulted in more uniform, large-scale formations.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Among further current important threats to Mediterranean landscapes are overdevelopment of coastal areas, abandonment of mountains and, as mentioned, the loss of variety via the reduction of traditional agricultural occupations.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The Mediterranean region is one of the most geologically active maritime areas of the globe, sitting on a complex tectonic boundary zone between the European and African plates.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The geology of the region, with the presence of plate boundaries and active faults, makes it prone to quite frequent earthquakes, tsunamis and submarine landslides with can have devastating consequences in densely populated coastal areas.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] In addition climate change now intensifies the frequency and impacts of storm surges and coastal flooding, putting additional human lives and property at risk.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Earthquakes are relatively frequent in the Mediterranean Basin, starting in the Mediterranean 70 million years ago.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] During the 20th century, 198,548 earthquake victims were recorded.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Volcanic eruptions are not uncommon either and left their mark in historical and archaeological records.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The largest include the Thera eruption, dated around 1600 BC, and the eruptions of Mount Vesuvius in 217 BC and AD 79 - the latter famously known for the destruction and the burying of the ancient cities of Pompeii and Herculaneum.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] In the same region the Phlegraean Fields west of Naples constitute one of the most significant volcanic systems in the world, still very active.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] In the same general area, volcanoes like Mt.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Etna and Stromboli are considered in a state of permanent activity, with frequent eruptions and lava emissions through the past 1500 years.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Tsunamis, usually triggered by earthquakes, volcanic eruptions and submarine landslides, have caused a number of documented disasters in the Mediterranean Basin in the past 2500 years.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Historical examples include the 365 and 1303 tsunamis in the Hellenic Arc, more recently the disastrous 1908 event that destroyed the cities of Messina and Reggio Calabria, and the large tsunami that occurred off the Algerian margin in 2003.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] On the diplomatic front, the experience of coastal countries and regional authorities is leading to exchange at the international level with the cooperation of NGOs, states, regional and municipal authorities.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The Greek–Turkish earthquake diplomacy is a quite positive example of natural hazards leading to improved relations between traditional rivals in the region after earthquakes in İzmit and Athens in 1999.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The European Union Solidarity Fund (EUSF) was set up to respond to major natural disasters and express European solidarity to disaster-stricken regions within all of Europe.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The largest amount of funding requests in the EU relates to forest fires, followed by floods and earthquakes.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Forest fires, whether human-made or natural, are a frequent and dangerous hazard in the Mediterranean region.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Tsunamis are also an often-underestimated hazard in the region.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] For example, the 1908 Messina earthquake and tsunami took more than 123,000 lives in Sicily and Calabria and were among the deadliest natural disasters in modern Europe.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Invasive species have become a major component of the Mediterranean ecosystem and have serious impacts on the Mediterranean ecology, endangering a number of local and endemic Mediterranean species.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] A first look at some groups of marine species shows that over 70% of exotic decapods and some 2/3 of exotic fishes found in the Mediterranean are of Indo-Pacific origin, introduced from the Red Sea via the Suez Canal.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] This makes the Canal the first pathway of arrival of alien species into the Mediterranean.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The impacts of some Lessepsian species have proven to be considerable, mainly in the Levantine basin of the Mediterranean, where they are replacing native species and becoming a familiar sight.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] When these species succeed in establishing populations in the Mediterranean Sea, compete with and begin to replace native species they are "Alien Invasive Species", as they are an agent of change and a threat to the native biodiversity.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] In the context of CBD, "introduction" refers to the movement by human agency, indirect or direct, of an alien species outside of its natural range (past or present).
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The Suez Canal, being an artificial (human-made) canal, is a human agency.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Lessepsian migrants are therefore "introduced" species (indirect, and unintentional).
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Whatever wording is chosen, they represent a threat to the native Mediterranean biodiversity, because they are non-indigenous to this sea.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] In recent years, the Egyptian government's announcement of its intentions to deepen and widen the Canal raised concerns from marine biologists, fearing that such an act will only worsen the invasion of Red Sea species into the Mediterranean, and lead to even more species passing through the Canal.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] In recent decades, the arrival of exotic species from the tropical Atlantic has become noticeable.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] In many cases this reflects an expansion – favoured by a warming trend of sub-tropical Atlantic waters, and also by a fast-growing maritime traffic – of the natural range of species that now enter the Mediterranean through the Strait of Gibraltar.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] While not as intense as Lessepsian migration, the process is of importance and is therefore receiving increased levels of scientific coverage.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] By 2100 the overall level of the Mediterranean could rise between 3 and 61 cm (1.2 and 24.0 in) as a result of the effects of climate change.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Coastal ecosystems also appear to be threatened by sea level rise, especially enclosed seas such as the Baltic, the Mediterranean and the Black Sea.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] These seas have only small and primarily east–west movement corridors, which may restrict northward displacement of organisms in these areas.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Sea level rise for the next century (2100) could be between 30 and 100 cm (12 and 39 in) and temperature shifts of a mere 0.05–0.1 °C (0.09–0.18 °F) in the deep sea are sufficient to induce significant changes in species richness and functional diversity.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Pollution in this region has been extremely high in recent years.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Many marine species have been almost wiped out because of the sea's pollution.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] One of them is the Mediterranean monk seal which is considered to be among the world's most endangered marine mammals.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The Mediterranean is also plagued by marine debris.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] A 1994 study of the seabed using trawl nets around the coasts of Spain, France and Italy reported a particularly high mean concentration of debris; an average of 1,935 items per km2 (5,010/sq mi).
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Largest ports of the Mediterranean area per total vessel traffic as of 2016.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Approximately 370,000,000 t (360,000,000 long tons) of oil are transported annually in the Mediterranean Sea (more than 20% of the world total), with around 250–300 oil tankers crossing the sea every day.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] An important destination is the Port of Trieste, the starting point of the Transalpine Pipeline, which covers 40% of Germany's oil demand (100% of the federal states of Bavaria and Baden-Württemberg), 90% of Austria and 50% of the Czech Republic.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Accidental oil spills happen frequently with an average of 10 spills per year.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] A major oil spill could occur at any time in any part of the Mediterranean.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The coast of the Mediterranean has been used for tourism since ancient times, as the Roman villa buildings on the Amalfi Coast or in Barcola show.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] From the end of the 19th century, in particular, the beaches became places of longing for many Europeans and travellers.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] From then on, and especially after World War II, mass tourism to the Mediterranean began with all its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] While initially, the journey was by train and later by bus or car, today the plane is increasingly used.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Tourism is today one of the most important sources of income for many Mediterranean countries, despite the human-made geopolitical conflicts in the region.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The countries have tried to extinguish rising human-made chaotic zones that might affect the region's economies and societies in neighbouring coastal countries, and shipping routes.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Naval and rescue components in the Mediterranean Sea are considered to be among the best due to the rapid cooperation between various naval fleets.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Unlike the vast open oceans, the sea's closed position facilitates effective naval and rescue missions, considered the safest and regardless of any human-made or natural disaster.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Tourism is a source of income for small coastal communities, including islands, independent of urban centres.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] However, tourism has also played a major role in the degradation of the coastal and marine environment.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Rapid development has been encouraged by Mediterranean governments to support the large numbers of tourists visiting the region, but this has caused serious disturbance to marine habitats by erosion and pollution in many places along the Mediterranean coasts.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Tourism often concentrates in areas of high natural wealth, causing a serious threat to the habitats of endangered species such as sea turtles and monk seals.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Reductions in natural wealth may reduce the incentive for tourists to visit.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Fish stock levels in the Mediterranean Sea are alarmingly low.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] The European Environment Agency says that more than 65% of all fish stocks in the region are outside safe biological limits.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] Some of the most important fisheries are threatened.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] There are clear indications that catch size and quality have declined, often dramatically, and in many areas, larger and longer-lived species have disappeared entirely from commercial catches.
[src:mediterranean/mediterranean-p02] A study showed that climate change-related exceptional marine heatwaves in the Mediterranean Sea during 2015–2019 resulted in widespread mass sealife die-offs in five consecutive years.
[src:mediterranean/noun] In grammar, a **noun** is a word that represents a concrete or abstract thing, like living creatures, places, actions, events, qualities, states of existence, and ideas.
[src:mediterranean/noun] To summarize this, nouns signify an object or idea.
[src:mediterranean/noun] A noun may serve as an object or subject within a phrase, clause, or sentence.
[src:mediterranean/noun] In linguistics, nouns constitute a lexical category (part of speech) defined according to how its members combine with members of other lexical categories.
[src:mediterranean/noun] The syntactic occurrence of nouns differs among languages.
[src:mediterranean/noun] In English, prototypical nouns are common nouns or proper nouns that can occur with determiners, articles and attributive adjectives, and can function as the head of a noun phrase.
[src:mediterranean/noun] According to traditional and popular classification, pronouns are distinct from nouns, but in much modern theory they are considered a subclass of nouns.
[src:mediterranean/noun] Every language has various linguistic and grammatical distinctions between nouns and verbs.
[src:mediterranean/noun] Word classes (parts of speech) were described by Sanskrit grammarians from at least the 5th century BC.
[src:mediterranean/noun] In Yāska's *Nirukta*, the noun (*nāma*) is one of the four main categories of words defined.
[src:mediterranean/noun] The Ancient Greek equivalent was *ónoma* (ὄνομα), referred to by Plato in the *Cratylus*, and later listed as one of the eight parts of speech in *The Art of Grammar*, attributed to Dionysius Thrax (2nd century BC).
[src:mediterranean/noun] The term used in Latin grammar was *nōmen*.
[src:mediterranean/noun] All of these terms for "noun" were also words meaning "name".
[src:mediterranean/noun] The English word *noun* is derived from the Latin term, through the Anglo-Norman *nom* (other forms include *nomme*, and *noun* itself).
[src:mediterranean/noun] The word classes were defined partly by the grammatical forms that they take.
[src:mediterranean/noun] In Sanskrit, Greek, and Latin, for example, nouns are categorized by gender and inflected for case and number.
[src:mediterranean/noun] Because adjectives share these three grammatical categories, adjectives typically were placed in the same class as nouns.
[src:mediterranean/noun] Similarly, the Latin term *nōmen* includes both nouns (substantives) and adjectives, as originally did the English word *noun*, the two types being distinguished as *nouns substantive* and *nouns adjective* (or *substantive nouns* and *adjective nouns*, or simply *substantives* and *adjectives*).
[src:mediterranean/noun] Many European languages use a cognate of the word *substantive* as the basic term for *noun* (for example, Spanish *sustantivo*, "noun").
[src:mediterranean/noun] Nouns in the dictionaries of such languages are demarked by the abbreviation *s.* or *sb.* instead of *n.*, which may be used for proper nouns or neuter nouns instead.
[src:mediterranean/noun] In English, some modern authors use the word *substantive* to refer to a class that includes both nouns (single words) and noun phrases (multiword units that are sometimes called *noun equivalents*).
[src:mediterranean/noun] It can also be used as a counterpart to *attributive* when distinguishing between a noun being used as the head (main word) of a noun phrase and a noun being used as a noun adjunct.
[src:mediterranean/noun] For example, the noun *knee* can be said to be used substantively in *my knee hurts*, but attributively in *the patient needed knee replacement*.
[src:mediterranean/noun] A noun can co-occur with an article or an attributive adjective.
[src:mediterranean/noun] In the following, an asterisk (*) in front of an example means that this example is ungrammatical.
[src:mediterranean/noun] Nouns have sometimes been characterized in terms of the grammatical categories by which they may be varied (for example gender, case, and number).
[src:mediterranean/noun] Such definitions tend to be language-specific, since different languages may apply different categories.
[src:mediterranean/noun] Nouns are frequently defined, particularly in informal contexts, in terms of their semantic properties (their meanings).
[src:mediterranean/noun] Nouns are described as words that refer to a *person*, *place*, *thing*, *event*, *substance*, *quality*, *quantity*, etc., but this manner of definition has been criticized as uninformative.
[src:mediterranean/noun] Several English nouns lack an intrinsic referent of their own: *behalf* (as in *on behalf of*), *dint* (*by dint of*), and *sake* (*for the sake of*).
[src:mediterranean/noun] Moreover, other parts of speech may have reference-like properties: the verbs *to rain* or *to mother*, or adjectives like *red*; and there is little difference between the adverb *gleefully* and the prepositional phrase *with glee*.
[src:mediterranean/noun] A functional approach defines a noun as a word that can be the head of a nominal phrase, i.e., a phrase with referential function, without needing to go through morphological transformation.
[src:mediterranean/noun] Nouns can have a number of different properties and are often sub-categorized based on various of these criteria, depending on their occurrence in a language.
[src:mediterranean/noun] Nouns may be classified according to morphological properties such as which prefixes or suffixes they take, and also their relations in syntax – how they combine with other words and expressions of various types.
[src:mediterranean/noun] Many such classifications are language-specific, given the obvious differences in syntax and morphology.
[src:mediterranean/noun] In English for example, it might be noted that nouns are words that can co-occur with definite articles (as stated at the start of this article), but this could not apply in Russian, which has no definite articles.
[src:mediterranean/noun] In some languages common and proper nouns have grammatical gender, typically masculine, feminine, and neuter.
[src:mediterranean/noun] The gender of a noun (as well as its number and case, where applicable) will often require agreement in words that modify or are used along with it.
[src:mediterranean/noun] In French for example, the singular form of the definite article is *le* for masculine nouns and *la* for feminine; adjectives and certain verb forms also change (sometimes with the simple addition of *-e* for feminine).
[src:mediterranean/noun] Grammatical gender often correlates with the form of the noun and the inflection pattern it follows; for example, in both Italian and Romanian most nouns ending in *-a* are feminine.
[src:mediterranean/noun] Gender can also correlate with the sex or social gender of the noun's referent, particularly in the case of nouns denoting people (and sometimes animals), though with exceptions (the feminine French noun *personne* can refer to a male or a female person).
[src:mediterranean/noun] In Modern English, even common nouns like *hen* and *princess* and proper nouns like *Alicia* do not have grammatical gender (their femininity has no relevance in syntax), though they denote persons or animals of a specific sex.
[src:mediterranean/noun] The gender of a pronoun must be appropriate for the item referred to: "The *girl* said the *ring* was from *her* new *boyfriend*, but *he* denied *it* was from *him*" (three nouns; and three gendered pronouns: or four, if this *her* is counted as a possessive pronoun).
[src:mediterranean/noun] Many nouns have both countable and uncountable uses; for example, *soda* is countable in "give me three sodas", but uncountable in "he likes soda".
[src:mediterranean/noun] Some nouns have both concrete and abstract meanings: *art* usually refers to something abstract ("Art is important in human culture"), but it can also refer to a concrete item ("I put my daughter's art up on the fridge").
[src:mediterranean/noun] A noun might have a literal (concrete) and also a figurative (abstract) meaning: "a brass *key*" and "the *key* to success"; "a *block* in the pipe" and "a mental *block*".
[src:mediterranean/noun] Similarly, some abstract nouns have developed etymologically by figurative extension from literal roots (*drawback*, *fraction*, *holdout*, *uptake*).
[src:mediterranean/noun] Many abstract nouns in English are formed by adding a suffix (*-ness*, *-ity*, *-ion*) to adjectives or verbs (*happiness* and *serenity* from the adjectives *happy* and *serene*; *circulation* from the verb *circulate*).
[src:mediterranean/noun] Illustrating the wide range of possible classifying principles for nouns, the Awa language of Papua New Guinea regiments nouns according to how *ownership* is assigned: as alienable possession or inalienable possession.
[src:mediterranean/noun] An alienably possessed item (a tree, for example) can exist even without a possessor.
[src:mediterranean/noun] But inalienably possessed items are necessarily associated with their possessor and are referred to differently, for example with nouns that function as kin terms (meaning "father", etc.), body-part nouns (meaning "shadow", "hair", etc.), or part–whole nouns (meaning "top", "bottom", etc.).
[src:mediterranean/noun] A noun phrase (or **NP**) is a phrase usually headed by a common noun, a proper noun, or a pronoun.
[src:mediterranean/noun] The head may be the only constituent, or it may be modified by determiners and adjectives.
[src:mediterranean/noun] For example, "The dog sat near Ms Curtis and wagged its tail" contains three NPs: *the dog* (subject of the verbs *sat* and *wagged*); *Ms Curtis* (complement of the preposition *near*); and *its tail* (object of *wagged*).
[src:mediterranean/noun] "You became their teacher" contains two NPs: *you* (subject of *became*); and *their teacher*.
[src:mediterranean/noun] For example, in the sentence "Gareth thought she was weird", the word *she* is a pronoun that refers to a person just as the noun *Gareth* does.
[src:mediterranean/noun] The word *one* can replace parts of noun phrases, and it sometimes stands in for a noun.
[src:mediterranean/noun] But *one* can also stand in for larger parts of a noun phrase.
[src:mediterranean/noun] For example, in the following example, *one* can stand in for *new car*.
[src:mediterranean/noun] Nominalization is a process whereby a word that belongs to another part of speech comes to be used as a noun.
[src:mediterranean/noun] This can be a way to create new nouns, or to use other words in ways that resemble nouns.
[src:mediterranean/noun] In French and Spanish, for example, adjectives frequently act as nouns referring to people who have the characteristics denoted by the adjective.
[src:mediterranean/noun] is a worldwide association of political parties.
